---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
---
<Base title="Adam Solove">
  <div class="page">
    <div class="titleblock">
      <p class="standfirst">
        I&rsquo;m a programmer, speaker and activist. I seek deep understanding
        so I can create clear explanations.
        <br><br>
      </p>
      <p class="positioning"></p>
    </div>

    <aside class="siderail">
      <h3>Elsewhere</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/asolove/">&#9656; LinkedIn</a>
        </li>
        <li><a href="/atom.xml">&#9656; RSS feed</a></li>
        <li>
          <a href="mailto:asolove@gmail.com">&#9656; Email</a>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </aside>

    <article class="body home">
      <h2 id="thinking" class="section-head">Talks &amp; essays</h2>

      <section class="entry">
        <div class="entry-body">
          <h3>The history of UI engineering</h3>
          <p>
            <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lIxbSDyHsXs"
            >Recreating Sketchpad, the first GUI</a>
            was a talk at <a href="https://bangbangcon.com/">!!con 2024</a>
            about what we can learn by studying and rebuilding early user
            interfaces. Earlier, <a
              href="/js/2013/10/15/constraint-programming-in-the-browser.html"
            >Constraint programming in the browser</a>
            at JSConf 2013 covered related ground, alongside a short note on
            <a href="/js/ui/2013/05/17/inspired-by-sketchpad.html"
            >being inspired by Sketchpad</a>
            and its constraint-oriented UI.
          </p>
        </div>
        <a
          class="entry-thumb"
          href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lIxbSDyHsXs"
        >
          <img
            src="/img/sketchpad-talk-preview.jpg"
            alt="Adam delivers a talk, gesturing at a podium in front of a screen showing the design of a rivet."
            loading="lazy"
          />
          <span class="thumb-credit">Fig. !!con 2024</span>
        </a>
      </section>

      <section class="entry">
        <div class="entry-body">
          <h3>Embeddable UIs</h3>
          <p>
            <a href="/js/2023/08/24/iframeable-finance.html"
            >&lt;iframe&gt;able finance</a>, presented at Fintech Devcon 2023,
            shares advice and war stories for building embeddable UIs and SDKs
            using iframes.
          </p>
        </div>
        <a class="entry-thumb" href="/js/2023/08/24/iframeable-finance.html">
          <img
            src="/img/iframeable-finance-talking.png"
            alt="Screenshot of Adam in purple hair, gesturing dynamically while presenting."
            loading="lazy"
          />
          <span class="thumb-credit">Fig. Fintech Devcon 2023</span>
        </a>
      </section>

      <section class="entry">
        <div class="entry-body">
          <h3>Collaborating to specify UIs</h3>
          <p>
            <a href="/js/ui/2017/07/14/pure-ui-control.html">Pure UI Control</a>
            is an essay on how teams can communicate and organize their work
            when building complex UIs. A companion essay,
            <a href="/js/ui/2017/04/21/important-problems-ui-engineering.html"
            >What are the important problems in UI engineering?</a>, sketches
            the open territory I think the field still hasn&rsquo;t properly
            mapped.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="entry">
        <div class="entry-body">
          <h3>Structuring concurrency</h3>
          <p>
            <a href="/js/ui/2017/04/01/synchronizable-abstractions.html"
            >Synchronizable abstractions for understandable concurrency</a>
            is an explanation of the Concurrent ML event system &mdash; the
            small, careful design that later inspired React Fiber.
          </p>
        </div>
        <a
          class="entry-thumb"
          href="/js/ui/2017/04/01/synchronizable-abstractions.html"
        >
          <img
            src="/img/cml.png"
            alt="Sequence diagram of Concurrent ML communication."
            loading="lazy"
          />
          <span class="thumb-credit">Fig. CML event sequence</span>
        </a>
      </section>

      <section class="entry">
        <div class="entry-body">
          <h3>React internals</h3>
          <p>
            <a href="/js/ui/2017/04/19/preact-in-pictures.html"
            >Preact in Pictures</a>
            is a 2017 talk explaining the core virtual <abbr
              title="Document object model"
            >DOM</abbr>
            diffing algorithm, following the code in Preact but with notes on
            how it compares to React. The companion
            <a href="/js/ui/2017/03/11/preact-internals-1.html"
            >Preact Internals</a>
            series goes deeper. Earlier, in 2014, I gave an early talk on
            <a href="/js/clojure/2014/05/08/react-js-and-om.html">React + Om</a>
            and wrote an
            <a href="/js/clojure/2014/01/06/om-experience-report.html"
            >experience report</a>
            on shipping a ClojureScript wrapper for React.
          </p>
        </div>
        <a class="entry-thumb" href="/js/ui/2017/04/19/preact-in-pictures.html">
          <img
            src="/img/preact-diagram.webp"
            alt="Diagram visualizing the Preact lifecycle."
            loading="lazy"
          />
          <span class="thumb-credit">Fig. Preact lifecycle</span>
        </a>
      </section>

      <section class="entry">
        <div class="entry-body">
          <h3>Web performance</h3>
          <p>
            <a href="/js/perf/2017/04/18/the-new-fast.html">The new fast</a>
            is a talk I gave several times in 2016 sharing advanced web
            performance techniques that were fairly new at the time &mdash;
            HTTP/2, server push, advanced CDN usage, and streaming responses.
          </p>
        </div>
        <a class="entry-thumb" href="/js/perf/2017/04/18/the-new-fast.html">
          <img
            src="/img/new-fast.png"
            alt="Slide with stylized network waterfall discussing site performance best practices."
            loading="lazy"
          />
          <span class="thumb-credit">Fig. The new fast</span>
        </a>
      </section>

      <h2 id="work" class="section-head">Work</h2>
      <p class="section-lede">
        Day-job software, mostly in narrow specialist domains where the cost of
        a misunderstanding is high.
      </p>

      <section class="entry">
        <div class="entry-body">
          <h3>Payments</h3>
          <p>
            My primary work for the past six years has been building UIs and
            APIs for payments. At <a href="https://www.figma.com/">Figma</a> I
            worked on payments and billing. At Stripe I worked on
            <a href="https://stripe.com/payments/elements">Elements</a>,
            <a href="https://stripe.com/blog/payment-api-design"
            >PaymentIntents</a>,
            <a href="https://stripe.com/guides/strong-customer-authentication"
            >SCA</a>,
            <a
              href="https://www.emvco.com/wp-content/uploads/news/EMVCo-FIDO-Alliance-W3C-Interest-Group-release_FINAL-website-version.pdf"
            >W3C</a>, and <a
              href="https://twitter.com/edwinwee/status/1141245532255313920"
            >emoji</a>.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="entry">
        <div class="entry-body">
          <h3>Design tools</h3>
          <p>
            From 2011&ndash;2017, I primarily worked on in-browser
            <abbr title="What you see is what you get">WYSIWYG</abbr> design
            tools for websites and images.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="entry">
        <div class="entry-body">
          <h3>Full history</h3>
          <p>
            A more complete chronological account lives on my
            <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/asolove/">LinkedIn profile</a>.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <h2 id="projects" class="section-head">Projects</h2>
      <p class="section-lede">
        Open-source and volunteer work &mdash; small collaborations that tend to
        outlast the season I spent on them.
      </p>

      <section class="entry">
        <div class="entry-body">
          <h3>Read Japanese Literature</h3>
          <p>
            <a href="https://readjapaneseliterature.com"
            >Read Japanese Literature</a>
            is a podcast and blog run by my partner, Alison. I help with the
            website and sound design.
          </p>
        </div>
        <a class="entry-thumb" href="https://readjapaneseliterature.com">
          <img
            src="/img/rjl.png"
            alt="Screenshot of the Read Japanese Literature blog page."
            loading="lazy"
          />
          <span class="thumb-credit">Fig. readjapaneseliterature.com</span>
        </a>
      </section>

      <section class="entry">
        <div class="entry-body">
          <h3>Pyret</h3>
          <p>
            <a href="https://pyret.org/index.html">Pyret</a> is an in-browser
            programming language and environment used in the
            <a href="https://www.bootstrapworld.org/blog/index.shtml"
            >Bootstrap curriculum</a>. In 2020 and &rsquo;21, I
            <a href="https://pyret.org/release-notes/summer-2021.html"
            >updated their IDE</a>
            to be shinier, faster, and easier to use.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="entry">
        <div class="entry-body">
          <h3>Federated Wiki</h3>
          <p>
            <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BdwLczSgvcc"
            >Federated Wiki</a>
            is a new, personal version of the wiki being developed by Ward
            Cunningham. In 2011, I collaborated with him to design and build the
            <a href="https://vimeo.com/32051583#">core UI paradigm</a>
            that still powers it today.<span class="end-mark">&#9632;</span>
          </p>
        </div>
        <a
          class="entry-thumb"
          href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BdwLczSgvcc"
        >
          <img
            src="/img/sfw.png"
            alt="Screenshot of Smallest Federated Wiki UI model."
            loading="lazy"
          />
          <span class="thumb-credit">Fig. Smallest Federated Wiki</span>
        </a>
      </section>
    </article>
  </div>
</Base>

<style>
/* Positioning paragraph under the standfirst */
.titleblock .positioning {
  font-family: var(--serif);
  font-size: 1.05rem;
  line-height: 1.5;
  color: var(--ink);
  max-width: 36rem;
  margin-bottom: 1.6rem;
}

/* Home-page body overrides: entries are full-width and use their
   own internal layout, not the body's paragraph constraint. They
   start at column 1 to align flush with the titleblock above. */
.body.home > .section-head,
.body.home > .section-lede,
.body.home > .entry,
.body.home > .end-rule {
  grid-column: 1 / -1;
  max-width: none;
}

.body.home .section-head {
  font-family: var(--sans);
  font-weight: 700;
  font-size: 1.6rem;
  line-height: 1.18;
  letter-spacing: -0.015em;
  margin-top: 2.2rem;
  margin-bottom: 0.4rem;
  padding-bottom: 0.4rem;
  border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule);
  display: flex;
  align-items: baseline;
  gap: 0.7em;
}
.body.home .section-head:first-child {
  margin-top: 0;
}
.body.home .section-head .section-label {
  font-family: var(--sans);
  font-size: 0.75rem;
  color: var(--spot);
  letter-spacing: 0.08em;
  text-transform: uppercase;
  font-weight: 400;
}

.body.home .section-lede {
  font-family: var(--serif);
  font-style: italic;
  font-size: 1.05rem;
  line-height: 1.45;
  color: var(--ink-soft);
  max-width: 38rem;
  margin: 0.6rem 0 1.6rem;
  font-variation-settings: "opsz" 28;
}

/* Entry: thumbnail on the left, body on the right. DOM order keeps
   the text first for screen readers; grid-template-areas places the
   thumb visually to the left of the body regardless of source order.

   When an entry has no thumb, the left cell is just empty space — body
   content still aligns at the same x as other entries' bodies, which
   keeps the vertical text column consistent down the page. */
.body.home .entry {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 12em 1fr;
  grid-template-areas: "thumb body";
  gap: 0 1.2rem;
  padding: 1.1rem 0;
  border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule-soft);
  align-items: start;
}
.body.home .entry:last-of-type {
  border-bottom: none;
}

.body.home .entry-body {
  grid-area: body;
  min-width: 0;
}
.body.home .entry-thumb {
  grid-area: thumb;
}
.body.home .entry-body h3 {
  font-family: var(--sans);
  font-weight: 600;
  font-size: 1.2rem;
  line-height: 1.22;
  letter-spacing: -0.008em;
  color: var(--ink);
  margin: 0 0 0.4rem;
}
.body.home .entry-body p {
  font-family: var(--serif);
  font-size: 1rem;
  line-height: 1.55;
  color: var(--ink);
  margin: 0;
  max-width: 36rem;
}
.body.home .entry-body a {
  color: var(--ink);
  border-bottom: 1px solid var(--spot);
  transition: background 0.15s;
}
.body.home .entry-body a:hover {
  background: var(--spot-wash);
}

.body.home .entry-thumb {
  display: block;
  align-self: start;
  /* Block link wrapping an image — opt out of the text-link underline. */
  text-decoration: none;
}
.body.home .entry-thumb img {
  width: 100%;
  display: block;
  background: white;
  border: 1px solid var(--rule-soft);
  /* outline sits outside the border without affecting layout, so the
     hover affordance doesn't reflow the surrounding entries. */
  outline: 0 solid transparent;
  transition: outline-width 0.15s, outline-color 0.15s;
}
.body.home .entry-thumb:hover img,
.body.home .entry-thumb:focus-visible img {
  outline: 2px solid var(--spot);
  outline-offset: 2px;
}
.body.home .entry-thumb .thumb-credit {
  display: block;
  font-family: var(--sans);
  font-size: 0.65rem;
  color: var(--ink-faint);
  margin-top: 0.3rem;
  letter-spacing: 0.04em;
}

/* When no thumbnail, the third column just stays empty — keeps
   the body column the same width across all entries for rhythm. */

.body.home .end-rule {
  text-align: center;
  color: var(--spot);
  font-size: 0.85rem;
  letter-spacing: 1em;
  padding-left: 1em;
  margin: 2.2rem 0 0.6rem;
}

/* On narrow screens, stack thumb above body. Cap the thumb width so
   it doesn't dominate; floating the body alongside it isn't worth
   the cramped column. */
@media (max-width: 980px) {
  .body.home .entry {
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    grid-template-areas:
      "thumb"
      "body";
  }
  .body.home .entry-thumb {
    margin-bottom: 0.8rem;
    max-width: 18rem;
  }
}
</style>
